data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected True, got False"). Modern MSTest has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|--------|-------|---------|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" instead of "False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows expected vs actual count |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Clearer intent, better failure message |

The `All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine as-is — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API, so `Assert.IsTrue` is appropriate there.

Also consider sealing the test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance, per MSTest best practices.
